# Next.js 16 Productivity App - Coding Rules & Best Practices

## Tech Stack Overview
- **Frontend**: Next.js 16 + React 19 + TypeScript + Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui
- **Backend**: Next.js API Routes + Prisma 5.22 ORM + Supabase PostgreSQL
- **Auth**: NextAuth.js
- **Deployment**: Vercel + Supabase
- **Validation**: Zod
- **Bundler**: Turbopack (default in Next.js 16)

## Next.js 16 Specific Best Practices

### üöÄ **Leverage Turbopack**
- Turbopack is now the default bundler in Next.js 16
- Significantly faster build times than Webpack
- Improved hot reloading and development experience
- No configuration needed - works out of the box

### ‚ö° **React Server Components (RSC) First**
- **Default to Server Components** for all static content
- Server Components run on the server, reducing client bundle size
- Only use Client Components (`'use client'`) for interactivity
- Compose Server and Client Components effectively

```typescript
// ‚úÖ RSC First Approach
export default function Dashboard() {
  // Server Component - runs on server
  return (
    <div>
      <ServerStats />
      <ClientInteractiveTimer /> {/* Only this needs 'use client' */}
    </div>
  );
}
```

### üéØ **Partial Prerendering (PPR)**
- New experimental feature for hybrid rendering
- Combines static generation with dynamic islands
- Enables better performance for mixed static/dynamic content
- Configure in `next.config.ts`:

```typescript
// next.config.ts
export default {
  experimental: {
    ppr: true, // Enable Partial Prerendering
  },
};
```

### üåê **Edge Runtime & Middleware**
- Use Edge Runtime for globally distributed functions
- Deploy middleware closer to users for better performance
- Ideal for authentication, redirects, and personalization

```typescript
